                <pb n="1"/>
                <p>My dear sir<lb/></p>
            <p>This morning a letter<lb/> comes signed by the President of the<lb/> Brooklyn Cong. where Friedlander<lb/> is officiating&#44; inviting me to a special<lb/> Congregational meeting&#44; Sunday 22 Inst. in<lb/> the school room etc.&#45;&#45;etc etc&#45;&#45;3. 30 p. m.<lb/></p>
            <p>Of course I&#39;ll go&#44; though it cuts<lb/> short my vacation&#45;&#45;Can you be present&#63;  If<lb/> not&#44; I would <del>&#91;&#63;&#93;</del> like to hear from you<lb/> what points you would emphasize against<lb/> him&#44;&#45;&#45;especially Bible&#45;points.<lb/></p>
            <p>From <del>2</del> 1 Chron. XXVIII v. 12. and v. 19. the arrange&#45;<lb/>ment of the courts is declared to be of other<lb/> than human origin.  But where can<lb/> you prove that there was a court of women<lb/> in that first temple&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>Yrs<lb/> H. Pereira Mendes<lb/>
                July 11&#47;88<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Rtn.<lb/>
                27W16<lb/>
                NewKent<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev Dr S Morais<lb/>
                546 N 5<lb/>
